The plans below show a harbour in 2000 and how it looks today.

Summarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.

Porth Harbour lies to the east of the main road. The plans juxtapose the harbour's layout in 2000 and today.

It is apparent from the plans that, with the exception of the addition of one dock, the harbour's outline has not changed much over the years. Some renovations have also taken place on the spit of land in the southern part of the harbour.

In 2000, Porth Harbour consisted of two docks on the north coast, two rectangular marinas on the west coast (the small one for private yachts and the big one for fishing boats), and two car parks and a shed for showers and toilets just between the main road and the marinas. In the south, a spit of land extends into the sea on which stood a disused castle with a public beach.

Today, a new dock has been added next to the older two. Also, the castle is converted to a hotel with its private beach. Another change is that the use of the two marinas has switched place: the big one is used for fishing boats now.